\f1\b \cf0 The ending screen
\f0\b0 \
This is where the title pays off. Regardless of outcome, the game generates the follow-up email: the entire 30-to-45-minute meeting summarized in two sentences. Under it: "This email took 40 seconds to read." Then your stats: minutes survived, minutes ADDED by coworkers, nods executed, action items dodged, words spoken (the lower the better).\

\f1\b Pacing
\f0\b0 \
In-game time at ~7x, so a clean 30-minute meeting is ~4.5 real minutes, ballooning toward 7 if tangents run wild. Silly play (nodding at everything, camera off the whole time, spamming "let's take this offline" until everyone hates you) ends runs fast, same shape as the Pivot Simulator.\

\f1\b Scope check
\f0\b0 \
One React artifact, same architecture as last time: a scripted transcript engine (beat structure with randomized filler lines per character), a tick loop, QTE windows, and modals for quizzes and hot potatoes. The transcript content is the biggest lift, roughly the size of the Pivot Simulator's event deck times two.\
One design decision to settle before building: how twitchy should this be? Option A leans arcade (tight nod timing windows, fast quiz timers, more QTEs) and rewards reflexes. Option B leans strategic (generous timers, fewer QTEs, more of the game in the zone-out/visibility economy and the hot potato standoffs). I'd lean B with a light sprinkle of A: the comedy is in the social resource management, and overly twitchy timing would fight the reading-the-transcript mechanic, which is the best idea in here.}